"Herrchen M., Keller D., Lepper P., Mangelsdorf I., Wahnschaffe U.","ELA 1.0 - A framework for life-cycle impact assessment developed by the Fraunhofer-Gesellschaft. Part A: The conceptual framework",1997,"Chemosphere","35","11",,"2589","2601",,,10.1016/S0045-6535(97)00334-2,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0030819295&partnerID=40&md5=2d4d2ba29ea30d29c705948029ab8c47","Fraunhofer-Inst. Environ. Chem./E., D-57392 Schmallenberg, Germany; Fraunhofer-Inst. Toxicol./Aerosol R., Nikolai-Fuchs Str. l, D-30625 Hannover, Germany","Herrchen, M., Fraunhofer-Inst. Environ. Chem./E., D-57392 Schmallenberg, Germany; Keller, D., Fraunhofer-Inst. Environ. Chem./E., D-57392 Schmallenberg, Germany; Lepper, P., Fraunhofer-Inst. Environ. Chem./E., D-57392 Schmallenberg, Germany; Mangelsdorf, I., Fraunhofer-Inst. Toxicol./Aerosol R., Nikolai-Fuchs Str. l, D-30625 Hannover, Germany; Wahnschaffe, U., Fraunhofer-Inst. Toxicol./Aerosol R., Nikolai-Fuchs Str. l, D-30625 Hannover, Germany","The Fraunhofer-Gesellschaft has sponsored the development of a conceptual and flexible, computer aided tool to perform the impact assessment within LCA (life cycle assessment) for technical products and processses. The developed general framework 'Ela 1.0' (environmental loads analysis) consists of four elements: the selection of appropriate impact categories, the categorization of emissions and wastes leaving the systems as well as of resource and energy consumption, the characterization and an analysis of the results of the impact assessment. The latter compares the product-based emissions with the total of emissions of a region such as Germany, the EU or OECD countries. The framework Ela 1.0 considers the environmental categories: global warming, ozone depletion, resource and energy consumption, wastes, eutrophication (including COD and BOD as measured parameters), acidification, ecotoxicity, ozone formation and human toxicity. The latter categories are handled by listing of precursors for ozone formation, and by listing of emissions scored according to their human hazard potential. The options, possibilities and limitations of the conceptual framework are presented in part A of a series of publications.",,"ozone; acidification; air pollution; article; biochemical oxygen demand; chemical oxygen demand; ecotoxicology; environmental impact assessment; eutrophication; germany; greenhouse effect; Acid Rain; Ecology; Environmental Monitoring; Environmental Pollutants; Europe; Greenhouse Effect; Humans; Industrial Waste; Models, Theoretical; Ozone; Software; Toxicity Tests; Gadus morhua",,"ozone, 10028-15-6; Acid Rain; Environmental Pollutants; Industrial Waste; Ozone, 10028-15-6",,,,"Heijungs, R., (1992) Environmental Life-cycle Assessment of Products, Guide (Part 1) and Backgrounds (Part 2), , CML, TNO, B&B, Leiden; Consoli, F., (1993) Guidelines for Life-cycle Assessment: A Code of Practice, Edition 1, , SETAC, Brussles; (1992) Ökobilanzen für Produkte: Bedeutung - Sachstand - Perspektiven, , UBA-Texte 38/92, Berlin; Ryding, S.O., Steen, B., EPS-systemet (1992) Institut för vatten och luftvardsforskning, IVL, Rapport B, 1022; Walz, R., Ecotoxicological impact assessment and the valuation step within LCA - Pragmatic approaches (1996) Int. J. Life Cycle Assessment, 1 (4); (1995) Statistisches Bundesamt Umweltökonomische Gesamtrechnung; (1995) Umweltbundesamt, , Daten zur Umwelt; Pressemitteilung des Statistischen Bundesamtes Abfallbilanz 25.1.1996(1991) Eurostat Umweltstatistik; (1994) Environmental Indicators OECD Core Set; (1995) Europe's Environmental Statistical Compendium for the Dobris Assessment; Emission Inventory in The Netherlands, RIVM 1994Statistisches Jahrbuch 1995 für das AuslandEurostat Statistische Grundzahlen der Europäischen Union 1995(1993) OECD Environmental Data; (1995) OECD Environmental Data; World Resources Institute 1992","Herrchen, M.; Fraunhofer-Inst Environm Chem Ecotox, D-57392 Schmallenberg, Germany",,,,,,,,00456535,,CMS